post_text: SHS Sophomore Samika Agarwal earned first placeart inthe Congressional Art Contest! She was selected unanimously and her art will be exhibited in the Canon Tunnel of the US Capitol. Samika has been invited to go to the ceremony in Washington D.C.The painting is primarily an oil painting with some acrylic parts. The theme is Hope During a Pandemic. Samika is also leading a project to paint our recycle bins to help inspire our students to sort their trash more effectively (whenever we return to school...)

CASA (Communities Against Substance Abuse) is committed to helping the youth in our community to lead safe and healthy lives and is seeking new Board members. Our programs and resources provide assistance to our schools, parents, community leaders and local agencies as we strive to inspire healthy choices from elementary school to middle school and through high school years.

To find out more information or discuss these opportunities, please contact Wendy Riggs wendy.riggs@gmail.com or Nancy Hernandez at wstrgaardn@aol.com.

post_text: The Saratoga High Orchestra program will be welcoming the Scotch College Orchestra from Hawthorn, Australia (near Melbourne) to CA and will share a cultural exchange and concert with our SHS Orchestra's at the Campbell Heritage Theater and Community Center in Campbell. The Synopsys Championship award ceremony was this weekend at the Campbell Theater. LGHS students collectively received: Four (4) first place category awards, Four (4) second place category awards, twelve (12) honorable mention category awards, Seven (7) special awards and three (3) top supporter fair awards.

Their outstanding recognition rate led to LGHS ranking 4th in the county in the outstanding school category and their teacher, Cathy Messenger, again ranking first in the outstanding science fair teacher award category.

post_text:
Congratulations to SHS's "Sea Devil” robot, shining at the Silicon Valley Regional robotics competition amd advancing to the World Championships in Houston, Texas and earning the Runner-up award for Safety, recognizing the team that progresses beyond safety fundamentals by using innovative ways to eliminate or protect against hazards AND being the SVR’s Engineering Inspiration Award WINNERS!
This was a goal our students had set for themselves at the beginning of this year and they worked very hard to accomplish it. This award celebrates outstanding success in advancing respect and appreciation for engineering within a team’s community. Special thanks to Sheeba Garg for her leadership, passion and hard work on behalf of our students and this program!

post_text: At the November 6, 2018 election, David Guidry and Peter L. Hertan were newly elected to the LGSUHSD Board of Trustees. Cynthia Chang was re-elected for another term. All three were sworn in at last night's meeting and we thank them for their leadership and support. Rosemary Rossi and Katherine Tseng are continuing on the Board. Katherine Tseng was elected Board President; Cynthia Chang as Vice-President; and Rosemary Rossi as Clerk. These five Trustees inspire with their commitment to our schools, students and community.

Los Gatos HS JNHS is hosting their Annual Haiku Holiday Film Faire and showing two powerful documentaries about Japan. This is A Fundraiser for California Wild Fire Victims and 親が育てられない子供を家庭に！里親連絡会 (Save the Abandoned Children in Japan) Please support our event! You can purchase tickets from this event website: https://yhara04.wixsite.com/hhfilmfaire

December 8th in the LGHS theater. Both films are raising cultural awareness and promoting diversity.

12:00 Doors open

12:30 - 1:00 Gambatte Kimashita (Eric Palmer) - the inspiring story of Japanese refugees who came to the Bay Area in the late 50's and 60's and built a community and successful industry in the Salinas Valley.

1:00 - 1:15 Q & A with Eric Palmer

1:15 - 2:00 intermission

2:00 - 3:25 Hafu

Award winning documentary about the mixed-race experience in Japan. https://youtu.be/6j_wQQZY-OE

Cityteam partnering with Saratoga High School Robotics team and Service Learning coordinator Tim Galleher to conduct a 5-day Graphic Design and 3-D Printing camp for students at Mayfair House. Research shows that only about 50% of kids entering high schools in low-income neighborhoods of Santa Clara County graduate. Mayfair House is in a neighborhood where 45% of families and 53% of kids live below the poverty level, 70% of the population is Hispanic and 63% of adults have earned a high school diploma or less.

These SHS students spent months preparing for the camp and teaching: Derek Chiou,Sohil Pokarna, Meghna Gupta,Suruchi Rastogi, Leena Elzeiny, Mitra Mokhlesi, Krisha Minocha, Colin Li, and Brandon Nguyen. These students are committed to making a difference- and it shows!

Six SHS alums and current students performed all summer with Drum Corps International Santa Clara Vanguard Cadets or Concord Blue Devils B Corps. The kids in red, Vanguard Cadets, won the World Championship on Tuesday for the DCI Open Class, and the Blue Devils B were right behind them in 2nd!
Two more SHS performances scheduled: World Championships in Indianapolis, Austin Shi (2018) and Alex Ruemler (2019), both with the Concord Blue Devils A Corps.

post_text: NUMU, the New Museum Los Gatos is hosting Wildcats Roadshow, an "Antiques Roadshow"-styled event on Saturday, May 19th. LGHS alumni and current students, teachers and staff are invited to bring their LGHS memorabilia and meet with our curatorial staff to select items and treasures for inclusion in the exhibition. KCAT, the local Los Gatos cable TV station is also going to be conducting interviews to record alumni stories and memories, again for inclusion in the exhibition.

The Parenting Continuum continues to offer opportunities for important discussions and provide support for parents and their students...

March 1, 7:00 p.m. - "Parenting Toward Positive Self-Image...Especially When Life Is Messy." Robin Massey shares her experiences with self and body image struggles, from mild unhappiness to eating disorders and depression, and offers ideas and perspectives on supporting our children towards acceptance and thriving.
March 20, 7:00 p.m. "Angst." A powerful documentary that explores anxiety: its causes, effects and what we can do about it.

post_text:
Our Board of Trustees serve four-year terms and commit their time and energy to serving the students of our district and representing the community that elects them and supports our schools. Each year, they seat a new slate of officers from amongst their members and I am happy to announce our new Board Officers for 2018, selected at the December 12th Board Meeting:
• Board President: Robin Mano
• Board Vice-President – Katherine Tseng
• Board Clerk – Cynthia Chang
Doug Ramezane and Rosemary Rossi will continue to serve as Trustees. I would also like to thank Rosemary for her service during 2017 as Board President.

Each year, they seat a new slate of officers from amongst their members and I am happy to announce our new Board Officers for 2018, selected at the December 12th Board Meeting:
• Board President: Robin Mano
• Board Vice-President – Katherine Tseng
• Board Clerk – Cynthia Chang
Doug Ramezane and Rosemary Rossi will continue to serve as Trustees. I would also like to thank Rosemary for her service during 2017 as Board President.

post_text: November 21st - an incredible event at SHS! A grand Gala Concert and Reception with the SHS Symphonic Wind Ensemble performing the World Premiere of composer James Stephenson’s epic new work, Mobius Trip for Saxophone and Wind Ensemble, with special Guest Soloist, Russell Kerns, whom also performed with the SHS Orchestra’s and Choirs. The entire 400+ Musicians of the SHS Music Department performed, with the Official Opening Reception of the newly built 24,000 square foot Music Building taking place immediately following the performance. Guided tours and entertainment for 1,000 guests were provided by current SHS Music Department Student Leadership students. Special thanks to SMB, supporters of the Measure E Bond and SHS music staff, Mr. Michael Boitz, Mr. Andrew Ford and Mr. Jason Shiuan!

post_text: On October 19, San Jose City Council Member, District 9, Don Rocha spoke to Middle College students about local government. Rocha has been speaking to the MC American Government students for five years. The students' questions and comments guide his presentation--this year the focus was on how the City of San Jose is addressing homelessness, affordable housing, traffic, and emergency responses. Rocha says the best way to contribute to the City is to be involved, ask questions, share ideas for solutions.
